article.description:
Nykesha Sales had 21 points and eight rebounds, and sparked a 19-4 run surge in the second half to lead
the host Connecticut Sun to a 73-63 victory Friday night over the Charlotte Sting.
article.headline: 19-4 run propels Connecticut; Charlotte 0-9 on road
article.linkText: Sun dispatch Sting, improve to 13-0 at home
article.story:
UNCASVILLE, Conn. (AP) -- It took the Connecticut Sun a while to
find their groove. Nykesha Sales pointed the way.

Sales had 21 points and eight rebounds, and sparked a 19-4 run
in the second half to lead the Sun to a 73-63 victory Friday night
over the lowly Charlotte Sting.

"It was our mind-set to play better basketball in the second
half and have everybody step it up," Sales said. "We fought
through the fatigue and fought through a pretty bad first half."

The Sting, last in the Eastern Conference, stayed even with the
conference leaders for most of the game. Connecticut was coming off
a grueling three-game road trip in four days that include
back-to-back games. The Sun looked weary at times, played sloppy in
spurts and couldn't seem to shake loose from the scrappy Sting.

"They're a team that is hungry. They have a bad record but they
are not a bad team," Sales said.

Dawn Staley, who led Charlotte with 15 points, hit consecutive
jumpers to put the Sting ahead 47-44 with 11:32 left. Sales took
over after that.

She had seven points, two boards and an inbounds steal in the
spurt that put Connecticut ahead for good. The surge included her
full-court pass to a streaking Lindsay Whalen, who converted on the
other end.

The Sting went scoreless for nearly five minutes down the
stretch.

"They changed defenses, trapped us and took us out of our
rhythm," Sting coach Trudi Lacey said. "We had a couple of
crucial turnovers and gave them some easy baskets, so it's hard to
recover from that."

The Sun (16-5) remain perfect at home, winning all eight games
this season at the Mohegan Sun Arena. They are 13-0 at home since
closing out last season with five straight wins.

The woes continue for the Sting (3-17), 0-9 on the road. Tammy
Sutton-Brown and Tangela Smith added 12 points apiece, and
Sutton-Brown had 11 rebounds.

It was the second meeting this week between the teams. The Sun
defeated the Sting 64-55 in Charlotte on Tuesday.

Whalen finished with 14 points and seven assists. Katie Douglas
added 13 points and reserve Asjha Jones 12 for the Sun.

"Our bench really gave us a lift of emotion to help us get back
in the game," Sun coach Mike Thibault said.

The teams were locked in a 30-all tie at the break after a
closely contested first half with four lead changes. The Sun led by
as many as six points in the half on a baseline layup by Sales for
a 16-10 lead.

Staley had nine points in the half for Charlotte. Her 3-pointer
with 9:16 left gave the Sting their largest lead at 22-18.

"I've been through many games in the NBA where teams are coming
off road trips and the first game at home is one of the uglier
games that they play," Thibault said. "There's a little bit of a
letdown. There's a little bit of `the home court will take care of
us.' It doesn't shoot a basketball. You've got to go play the game
yourself."
